    "original_title": "Acute watery diarrhoea claims lives among drought-hit rural families in Kismayo",
    "slug": "acute-watery-diarrhea-outbreak-kills-seven-in-rural-lower-juba",
    "summary": "Seven people have died and over 230 others have been infected in an acute watery diarrhea outbreak in Bula Haji, 90 km west of Kismayo, since mid-June. Displaced families and pastoralists lack access to clean water and healthcare.",
    "content": "An outbreak of acute watery diarrhea in the Bula Haji area, located about 90 kilometers west of Kismayo in Somalia's Lower Juba region, has resulted in seven deaths and 235 infections since mid-June, according to volunteer doctors providing emergency treatment. The affected population includes displaced families and pastoralists residing in remote settlements where safe drinking water and medical facilities are scarce. Many residents rely on untreated water from shallow wells, with the nearest hospital a long distance away in Kismayo.\n\nThe outbreak highlights the ongoing vulnerabilities faced by communities hit by drought, which have forced many to abandon their homes in search of water and pasture. These conditions have created an environment where waterborne diseases can spread rapidly. Dr. Hassan Hussein Mohamed, a volunteer doctor involved in the response, noted that the lack of sanitation and hygiene education exacerbates the crisis.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this tragedy underscores the urgent need for sustainable water and health infrastructure in rural areas. Many diaspora members send remittances to relatives in these regions, but such funds often cannot address foundational issues like access to clean water. The outbreak also serves as a reminder of the persistent health emergencies that follow drought cycles, which have become more frequent due to climate change.\n\nThe response has been hampered by limited resources, with volunteer doctors working without adequate supplies or support. International aid organizations have been slow to respond, leaving local communities to cope as best they can. This situation reflects a broader pattern in Somalia, where remote areas are often overlooked in favor of more accessible urban centers.\n\nAs drought conditions continue to worsen, the risk of further disease outbreaks remains high. The Somali diaspora can play a role by supporting initiatives that build local capacity for water purification and primary healthcare. However, long-term solutions require sustained investment from both Somali authorities and international partners.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Ergo here: https://radioergo.org/en/2026/07/acute-watery-diarrhoea-claims-lives-among-drought-hit-rural-families-in-kismayo/",
